ðŸŸ© Problem
- You need to build two stacks inside one shared array.  
- Stack 1 grows from the left. Stack 2 grows from the right.  
- They can expand until both tops meet. If thereâ€™s no free space left, the push should be ignored.  
- Pop operations should print the popped value.  
- Invalid operations print nothing.


ðŸŸ© Sample Input
6
1 10
1 20
2 30
2 40
3
4
-1

ðŸŸ© Sample Output
20
40


ðŸŸ© Solution (Two Stacks in One Array)

import java.util.*;
public class Solution {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        int n = sc.nextInt();
        int[] arr = new int[n];

        int top = -1;      
        int end = n;       

        while (true) {

            int ip = sc.nextInt();

            if (ip == -1) break;

            // push1 x
            if (ip == 1) {
                int x = sc.nextInt();
                if (top + 1 < end) {
                    arr[++top] = x;
                }
            }

            // push2 x
            else if (ip == 2) {
                int x = sc.nextInt();
                if (top + 1 < end) {
                    end--;
                    arr[end] = x;
                }
            }

            // pop1
            else if (ip == 3) {
                if (top >= 0) {
                    System.out.println(arr[top]);
                    top--;
                }
            }

            // pop2
            else if (ip == 4) {
                if (end < n) {
                    System.out.println(arr[end]);
                    end++;
                }
            }
        }
    }
}


ðŸŸ© Time Complexity - O(1) per operation â€” push and pop are constant time
ðŸŸ© Space Complexity - O(n) â€” both stacks share one array of size n
